snippet.textDisplay: Some observations about this song, the singers, and the ongoing dialog from someone who has lived in Orissa and is quite familiar with Indian history.1. Great composition and a superb performance by the singer2. Rapper that sings "Vande Utkala Janani ..." looks and sings like a shrunk down version of Snoop Dog. Please consider that a compliment3. Sambalpuri is not a language - it is an offshoot dialect of the Oriya language spoken by the people that identify themselves as being from Orissa as much as say a Cajun in Louisiana is very much an American speaking English. A language, unlike a dialect, has to have a unique script of its own; Sambalpuri does not have a script different from the Oriya language. Undoubtedly, you may have to strain yourself a bit to understand Sambalpuri if you have a reasonable grasp of Oriya, and invariably some words will be alien. 4. It is amazing that Oriya and Bengali are different languages - understandably so because of having vastly different scripts - but with phonetic commonality to the point that an individual well versed in one can understand the basics of the other with a little effort; in my opinion similar to the commonality between Norwegian and Swedish.5. Orissa is a beautiful state, perhaps one of the few left in India that has the lush forests memorialized by Kipling. It's people personify an unpretentious simplicity that has not been diluted by the ages; most favorably compared to Ireland - what you see is what you get6. Knowing the meaning of "Vande Utkala Janani...," it is rather easy to see why the ancients of Utkala (Orissa) went to war with the Magadha empire circa 300 BC. I am pretty sure that "Vande Utkala..." had not been formalized in 300 BC, but I suspect the people of Kalinga felt pretty strongly about their sovereignty/state
